1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:18,815
Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa

2
00:00:18,795 --> 00:00:33,671
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:39,457 --> 00:00:47,807
I thought I'd choose this word karuna, which translates pretty directly as compassion.

4
00:00:49,372 --> 00:00:59,865
Our word sort of gives us some sort of idea of how we should develop that virtue.

5
00:00:59,905 --> 00:01:04,170
Our word comes from the Latin, doesn't it?

6
00:01:04,250 --> 00:01:05,671
Patio, which means I suffer.

7
00:01:07,393 --> 00:01:09,695
The commies with, to suffer with somebody.

8
00:01:10,537 --> 00:01:12,259
You have to be slightly careful about that.

9
00:01:13,792 --> 00:01:17,799
The first thing to say is that the direct enemy of it is cruelty.

10
00:01:19,001 --> 00:01:21,424
Cruelty is the desire to make somebody suffer.

11
00:01:23,308 --> 00:01:27,114
Compassion is defined as the desire to alleviate suffering.

12
00:01:27,474 --> 00:01:28,396
It's as simple as that.

13
00:01:29,658 --> 00:01:31,600
The desire to alleviate suffering.

14
00:01:32,623 --> 00:01:35,447
Physical, mental, financial, existential.

15
00:01:36,248 --> 00:01:38,111
It's the desire to alleviate suffering.

16
00:01:40,757 --> 00:01:45,905
And it's got a couple of very sort of subtle enemies.

17
00:01:46,185 --> 00:01:48,468
That's how the commentaries would put it.

18
00:01:48,489 --> 00:01:49,650
Near and far enemy.

19
00:01:51,813 --> 00:01:54,397
So the near one is, you know, is cruelty.

20
00:01:55,438 --> 00:02:00,784
But the one that's more subtle, the one that we don't see is, one of them is the do-gooder.

21
00:02:03,069 --> 00:02:09,296
So the do-gooder is somebody who's going to do you the good they want to do you, no matter what you want.

22
00:02:13,140 --> 00:02:18,406
It may be that a friend has fallen ill or something, so you think to yourself, well, I'll go and visit.

23
00:02:20,168 --> 00:02:26,435
And I don't know whether people do it these days, but they've got some grapes and lucasade or something.

24
00:02:26,455 --> 00:02:26,914
Some soup.

25
00:02:28,537 --> 00:02:33,581
And when you get there, of course, they say, oh, I've been really sick.

26
00:02:33,641 --> 00:02:37,165
I've just vomited all over the toilet.

27
00:02:37,186 --> 00:02:38,187
I can't possibly eat it.

28
00:02:39,263 --> 00:02:41,609
I said, oh, I'm sorry, you know, it must be very bad.

29
00:02:41,628 --> 00:02:42,771
He said, could you do me a favour?

30
00:02:42,831 --> 00:02:44,657
I said, do you think you could clean the toilet?

31
00:02:48,406 --> 00:02:54,200
And while you're cleaning it, he said, I came here with soup and I'm cleaning a blooming toilet.

32
00:02:55,835 --> 00:03:03,304
And it's that, what compassion is, is of course to stand in the other person's shoes and to ask them what they want.

33
00:03:03,625 --> 00:03:12,515
So you don't go there with some pre-set ideas, some set position of how you're going to help them.

34
00:03:14,497 --> 00:03:24,711
There's a lovely case of that, of a charity in Totnes, that decided to collect clothes and send them to Africa, to this place in Africa.

35
00:03:26,193 --> 00:03:29,677
When they got there, the tailor trade collapsed.

36
00:03:30,057 --> 00:03:31,259
And with it, the local economy.

37
00:03:31,800 --> 00:03:33,102
So they had to pull all the clothes back.

38
00:03:35,626 --> 00:03:37,829
It was a case of compassion without wisdom.

39
00:03:39,431 --> 00:03:42,074
So that do-gooding, you have to be careful of that.

40
00:03:42,093 --> 00:03:50,385
So it's the case of if you see somebody who needs help, it's like your first question is, what do you want me to do?

41
00:03:51,006 --> 00:03:52,908
Then, of course, there can be some bargaining, you know.

42
00:03:54,121 --> 00:03:55,103
I want you to give me £100,000.

43
00:03:55,143 --> 00:04:00,872
There might be some bit of bargaining going on before.

44
00:04:00,893 --> 00:04:03,818
It's not because they are something you have to do it.

45
00:04:04,218 --> 00:04:08,227
I mean, you've also got to take into consideration your own situation.

46
00:04:08,247 --> 00:04:10,050
But that's your starting position.

47
00:04:10,471 --> 00:04:13,475
You don't presume that you know what the other person wants.

48
00:04:13,817 --> 00:04:17,884
And that undermines this more subtle mistake that we make of being a do-gooder.

49
00:04:20,327 --> 00:04:24,814
The other one is a bit more offensive in a way, and that's pity, isn't it?

50
00:04:25,815 --> 00:04:28,579
You know, oh, poor thing, you must be suffering.

51
00:04:28,620 --> 00:04:30,081
I know how you feel.

52
00:04:30,141 --> 00:04:35,209
It's coming from this sort of high position, you know.

53
00:04:35,870 --> 00:04:37,091
I mean, consider yourself.

54
00:04:39,675 --> 00:04:49,069
If you've fallen over, for instance, and you're there with a broken leg, you know, somebody comes, oh, poor thing, must be really hurting.

55
00:04:50,584 --> 00:04:54,608
All you want to do is call the ambulance.

56
00:04:54,629 --> 00:04:57,211
So this pity distances us from the suffering.

57
00:04:57,552 --> 00:05:00,815
It puts us, shall we say, slightly above it.

58
00:05:03,559 --> 00:05:04,339
It's a conceit.

59
00:05:06,802 --> 00:05:19,596
So, to undermine that, again, one has to slip into the other person's shoes by way of just an imaginative force, like, if I was in that position, what would I want?

60
00:05:19,617 --> 00:05:19,697
See?

61
00:05:22,899 --> 00:05:33,956
So these different positions, they're in us, all of us are a bit of a do-gooder, a bit of cruelty here and there.

62
00:05:34,055 --> 00:05:40,785
And it's a case of just recognizing that these are conditionings within us.

63
00:05:40,805 --> 00:05:54,887
When they come up and if you find yourself blaming yourself, accusing yourself of cruelty and you could have been more sensitive and all that sort of stuff, then you're being cruel to yourself, being compassionate to yourself.

64
00:05:54,906 --> 00:06:01,276
There's a case also of being able to forgive oneself and just to recognize these are all conditionings.

65
00:06:02,370 --> 00:06:21,949
and you learn from those mistakes don't you so the next time we find ourselves in a similar position one remembers that so then you you make the right intention you see and the intention is to be with the person who's suffering and ask what they want of you

66
00:06:24,798 --> 00:06:26,502
In that way you can develop this Karuna.

67
00:06:26,863 --> 00:06:30,235
And Karuna, this compassion, remember, is one of the illimitables.

68
00:06:30,394 --> 00:06:34,668
It's indefinite as to how much it can be developed within you.

69
00:06:35,672 --> 00:06:38,942
So long as we're alive and breathing, you can develop Karuna.

70
00:06:42,516 --> 00:06:46,100
So, I mean, this particular time, it's a time of goodwill, isn't it?

71
00:06:47,362 --> 00:06:49,444
Often you get charities come, you see.

72
00:06:49,605 --> 00:06:54,009
So there's a stepping into the other person's shoes.

73
00:06:54,730 --> 00:06:55,932
And then one does what one can.

74
00:06:55,951 --> 00:06:58,153
You don't have to give to every charity that comes along.

75
00:06:58,254 --> 00:07:01,137
There's hundreds of millions of them.

76
00:07:01,158 --> 00:07:06,043
But it's a case of, you know, doing what you can for the other.

77
00:07:06,935 --> 00:07:08,497
There's limitations, aren't there?

78
00:07:08,516 --> 00:07:10,060
Just limitations.

79
00:07:10,079 --> 00:07:16,290
If you feel guilty about not being able to help people, that's ridiculous.

80
00:07:16,310 --> 00:07:17,791
You can only do what you can do, you see.

81
00:07:18,533 --> 00:07:22,800
You've only got so much power, so much wealth, so much influence.

82
00:07:25,884 --> 00:07:34,533
If somebody is dying of a heart attack and you're not a doctor and you don't know what to do, you can't blame yourself for it.

83
00:07:34,552 --> 00:07:39,387
All you can do is witness it, is to be a companion in that suffering, isn't it?

84
00:07:42,000 --> 00:08:05,309
So we have to be, there's all sorts of little mistakes we can make around this area of compassion and it's just a case of making that aware of, making that, you know, something that we're aware of and making sure that whenever we want to do something for somebody or give some of our wealth towards somebody, that we have a very clear intention in mind.

85
00:08:05,709 --> 00:08:06,110
That's all.

86
00:08:09,074 --> 00:08:11,956
Remember that all our conditionings start with intention.

87
00:08:14,029 --> 00:08:18,059
Once you have the right intention, at least that's your main karmic line.

88
00:08:18,259 --> 00:08:19,622
Karma here means conditioning.

89
00:08:21,966 --> 00:08:25,795
So even though the old stuff may come up, you've not actually reinforced it.

90
00:08:26,216 --> 00:08:26,978
So that's the point.

91
00:08:27,800 --> 00:08:30,165
And just very slowly one shifts, one moves over.

92
00:08:39,089 --> 00:08:41,864
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

93
00:08:42,267 --> 00:08:46,871
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.

